HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1075
By Jones J
A RESOLUTION to recognize and commend the Nashville
Humane Association on the occasion of its
eightieth anniversary.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should recognize
those exemplary facilities that, through an abiding commitment to excellence, have
distinguished themselves as community leaders of whom we can all be proud; and
WHEREAS, one such estimable practice is the Nashville Humane Association (NHA),
which is celebrating its eightieth anniversary of dedicated service to the citizens and animals of
Nashville and Davidson County; and
WHEREAS, one of the oldest service organizations in Nashville, NHA was founded in
1887 to protect children from inhumane working conditions and draft horses from mistreatment;
the association as it is known today was incorporated in 1946 to protect the well-being of
animals; and
WHEREAS, NHA is committed to finding responsible homes, controlling pet
overpopulation, and promoting the humane treatment of animals; the organization has spent
four decades fighting to help homeless, at-risk, and adoptable pets in Nashville, throughout
Middle Tennessee, and across the globe; and
WHEREAS, an important member of the community, NHA provides pathways for animal
adoption as well as ways to foster animals and volunteer and has hosted a variety of events to
support its endeavors, including Unleashed, Mutt Strut 5K, Cause for Paws, and Dog Day
Festival; and
WHEREAS, NHA also offers low-cost vaccine and spay/neuter clinics, Nashville's first
twenty-four-hour microchip scanner, a pet food bank, foster care opportunities, and educational
resources for pet owners and the broader community; and
HJR1075
014466
- 1 -

WHEREAS, the organization partners with agencies such as Metro Animal Care and
Control to support at-risk animals and save furry lives across the community; in 2024 alone, the
organization placed 3,139 dogs and cats into forever homes, maintained an impressive ninety-
nine percent save rate—well above the national benchmark for no-kill shelters—and facilitated
3,187 medical procedures for pets in need; and
WHEREAS, guided by the steady leadership of Executive Director Laura Baker and
strengthened by committed board members like Robin Patton, NHA enters its ninth decade with
both momentum and purpose, prepared to meet the evolving needs of animals and the
community that cares for them; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor and commend the Nashville Humane Association on the
celebration of its eightieth anniversary, thank its staff for their unwavering dedication to animal
health and welfare, and extend our best wishes for continued success in the years to come.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
